---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
import "../css/projects.css";
// Wildlife Rescue Platform — Case Study
---

<Layout>
  <header class="project-header">
    <h1 class="page__title">Wildlife Rescue &amp; Operations Platform</h1>
    <p class="page__subtitle">Solutions Engineering &amp; System Design</p>
  </header>

  <!-- 1. Problem & Goals -->
  <section class="section__container">
    <h2 class="section__title">1. Problem &amp; Goals</h2>
    <p class="section__intro">
      Wildlife rescue efforts are hindered by fragmented coordination, delayed
      response times, and inconsistent data handling across multiple actors. The
      goal is to streamline operations, improve response efficiency, ensure data
      reliability, and increase transparency and engagement while maintaining
      high system availability.
    </p>

    <ul class="section__list --parent">
      <li class="section__item">
        Wildlife rescue efforts suffer from fragmented coordination, delayed
        responses, and inconsistent data
      </li>
      <li class="section__item">
        Operational challenges:
        <ul class="section__list">
          <li class="section__item">
            Delays caused by unstructured reporting, such as phone calls and
            social media messages
          </li>
          <li class="section__item">
            Lack of centralized, real-time operational visibility
          </li>
          <li class="section__item">
            Volunteer coordination is inefficient and error-prone
          </li>
          <li class="section__item">
            Medical records are inconsistent and not standardized
          </li>
          <li class="section__item">
            Donation tracking lacks transparency, reducing trust
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li class="section__item">
        Goals:
        <ul class="section__list">
          <li class="section__item">
            Reduce response time to &lt; 2 hours from 4–6 hours
          </li>
          <li class="section__item">
            Increase volunteer participation to &gt; 75%
          </li>
          <li class="section__item">
            Ensure &gt; 90% data completeness for reports and medical records
          </li>
          <li class="section__item">
            Improve donation transparency to &gt; 90% traceability
          </li>
          <li class="section__item">Increase public engagement to &gt; 60%</li>
          <li class="section__item">Maintain system uptime &gt; 99%</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <!-- 2. Context & Constraints -->
  <section class="section__container">
    <h2 class="section__title">2. Context &amp; Constraints</h2>
    <p class="section__intro">
      The system operates within a complex, multi-actor environment involving
      citizens, NGOs, volunteers, and authorities, with real-world, non-linear
      workflows. It must be built under technical and operational constraints
      such as a modular monolith architecture, limited resources, and a small
      team, while ensuring practicality and adoption.
    </p>

    <ul class="section__list --parent">
      <li class="section__item">
        Environment:
        <ul class="section__list">
          <li class="section__item">
            Multi-actor ecosystem involving citizens, NGOs, volunteers, and
            authorities
          </li>
          <li class="section__item">Real-world, non-linear rescue workflows</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li class="section__item">
        Technical constraints:
        <ul class="section__list">
          <li class="section__item">Modular monolith architecture</li>
          <li class="section__item">MongoDB for flexible schema design</li>
          <li class="section__item">Limited external integrations</li>
          <li class="section__item">Cloud-agnostic design</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li class="section__item">
        Operational constraints:
        <ul class="section__list">
          <li class="section__item">Small engineering team, solo-driven</li>
          <li class="section__item">MVP scope limited to core modules</li>
          <li class="section__item">Timeline: 6–12 months</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li class="section__item">
        Assumptions:
        <ul class="section__list">
          <li class="section__item">Users have internet access</li>
          <li class="section__item">
            NGOs adopt the system if efficiency improves
          </li>
          <li class="section__item">
            Transparency increases public engagement
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li class="section__item">
        Field and medical professionals are separated because they represent
        different operational roles with distinct workflows and data structures.
      </li>
      <li class="section__item">
        If needed, they can be grouped into a single “Operational User” at this
        level and differentiated in Level 2 or Level 3 diagrams.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <img src="/images/stw2_2.c1.webp" alt="C1 diagram" />
  </section>

  <!-- 3. Users & Requirements -->
  <section class="section__container">
    <h2 class="section__title">3. Users &amp; Requirements</h2>
    <p class="section__intro">
      The platform supports diverse user roles with distinct responsibilities,
      requiring a balance between flexibility and structured workflows. It must
      provide core operational capabilities while meeting performance, security,
      scalability, and usability requirements for real-world usage.
    </p>

    <ul class="section__list --parent">
      <li class="section__item">
        Users:
        <ul class="section__list">
          <li class="section__item">
            General users: report incidents and track updates
          </li>
          <li class="section__item">Volunteers: join and execute tasks</li>
          <li class="section__item">
            Organization staff: manage operations and records
          </li>
          <li class="section__item">Donors: fund and track campaigns</li>
          <li class="section__item">Admins: system control and monitoring</li>
          <li class="section__item">Authorities: analytics and compliance</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li class="section__item">
        Functional requirements:
        <ul class="section__list">
          <li class="section__item">Incident reporting and tracking</li>
          <li class="section__item">Operations and medical management</li>
          <li class="section__item">Campaign and donation tracking</li>
          <li class="section__item">User management with RBAC</li>
          <li class="section__item">Notifications system</li>
          <li class="section__item">Analytics dashboards</li>
          <li class="section__item">External API integrations</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li class="section__item">
        Non-functional requirements:
        <ul class="section__list">
          <li class="section__item">Performance: &lt; 3s response time</li>
          <li class="section__item">Scalability: 10,000+ concurrent users</li>
          <li class="section__item">
            Security: RBAC, TLS, and encryption at rest
          </li>
          <li class="section__item">Availability: &gt; 99.5% uptime</li>
          <li class="section__item">
            Data integrity: consistent and auditable
          </li>
          <li class="section__item">
            Accessibility: multilingual and WCAG compliant
          </li>
          <li class="section__item">Maintainability: modular structure</li>
          <li class="section__item">Auditability: full change tracking</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ul>

    <div class="subsection__container">
      <h3 class="subsection__title">Incident Reporting Flow</h3>
      <img src="/images/stw2_3.flow1.webp" alt="C1 diagram" />
    </div>

    <div class="subsection__container">
      <h3 class="subsection__title">Medical Professional Operation Flow</h3>
      <img src="/images/stw2_3.flow2.webp" alt="C1 diagram" />
    </div>

    <div class="subsection__container">
      <h3 class="subsection__title">Organization Management</h3>
      <p class="">Handles verification and creation of organizations.</p>
      <img src="/images/stw2_3.flow3.webp" alt="C1 diagram" />
    </div>

    <div class="subsection__container">
      <h3 class="subsection__title">Team Management</h3>
      <p class="section__intro">Defines how teams are structured and linked.</p>
      <img src="/images/stw2_3.flow4.webp" alt="C1 diagram" />
    </div>

    <div class="subsection__container">
      <h3 class="subsection__title">Member Management</h3>
      <p class="section__intro">Controls membership and role assignment.</p>
      <img src="/images/stw2_3.flow5.webp" alt="C1 diagram" />
    </div>

    <div class="subsection__container">
      <h3 class="subsection__title">Donation Flow</h3>
      <img src="/images/stw2_3.flow6.webp" alt="C1 diagram" />
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- 4. System Overview -->
  <section class="section__container">
    <h2 class="section__title">4. System Overview</h2>
    <p class="section__intro">
      The platform supports the full lifecycle of wildlife rescue coordination,
      from public incident reporting to field response, medical follow-up,
      organizational management, and donation campaign support.
    </p>
    <p class="section__intro">
      At a high level, the system receives user actions through the web
      application, validates and processes the submitted information, updates
      the relevant records, and triggers follow-up actions such as
      notifications, task assignment, campaign updates, or status changes.
    </p>
    <p class="section__intro">
      This section focuses on system behavior, not on the internal technical
      architecture.
    </p>

    <ul class="section__list --parent">
      <li class="section__item">
        Incident reporting:
        <ul class="section__list">
          <li class="section__item">
            Public users submit wildlife incident reports with location,
            description, and supporting details
          </li>
          <li class="section__item">
            The system validates the report, stores it, and makes it available
            for review or assignment
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li class="section__item">
        Rescue operation coordination:
        <ul class="section__list">
          <li class="section__item">
            Field professionals and operators review reports, update rescue
            status, and coordinate actions
          </li>
          <li class="section__item">
            The system tracks operation progress and keeps relevant users
            informed
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li class="section__item">
        Medical workflow:
        <ul class="section__list">
          <li class="section__item">
            Medical professionals update animal condition, treatment
            information, and recovery status
          </li>
          <li class="section__item">
            The system links medical updates to the related animal case and
            operation
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li class="section__item">
        Donation campaign support:
        <ul class="section__list">
          <li class="section__item">
            Donors support campaigns related to wildlife rescue or
            organizational needs
          </li>
          <li class="section__item">
            The system coordinates campaign status with an external donation
            platform
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li class="section__item">
        Notifications and status updates:
        <ul class="section__list">
          <li class="section__item">
            The system sends relevant updates based on report, operation,
            donation, or campaign events
          </li>
          <li class="section__item">
            Public and internal visibility may differ depending on role and
            permissions
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ul>

    <div class="subsection__container">
      <h3 class="subsection__title">High-level System Flow Overview</h3>

      <h4 class="subsection__subtitle">
        Workflow — Incident Intake and Case Routing
      </h4>
      <img src="/images/stw2_4.workflow1.webp" alt="C1 diagram" />

      <h4 class="subsection__subtitle">
        Workflow — Rescue Operation &amp; Medical Follow-up
      </h4>
      <img src="/images/stw2_4.workflow2.webp" alt="C1 diagram" />
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- 5. Architecture -->
  <section class="section__container">
    <h2 class="section__title">5. Architecture</h2>
    <p class="section__intro">
      The platform is designed as a web-based system composed of a frontend
      application, a backend API, a database, supporting infrastructure, and
      external integrations.
    </p>
    <p class="section__intro">
      The backend follows a <strong>modular monolith architecture</strong>. This
      keeps the system easier to maintain while avoiding the operational
      complexity of microservices at the MVP stage.
    </p>

    <ul class="section__list --parent">
      <li class="section__item">
        Architecture style:
        <ul class="section__list">
          <li class="section__item">Modular monolith</li>
          <li class="section__item">
            Keeps related business logic in one deployable backend application
          </li>
          <li class="section__item">
            Separates domains through modules and service layers
          </li>
          <li class="section__item">
            Avoids premature microservice complexity
          </li>
          <li class="section__item">
            Allows future extraction of specific modules if scale requires it
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li class="section__item">
        Main containers:
        <ul class="section__list">
          <li class="section__item">
            <strong>Frontend — Astro:</strong> user interface for public users, professionals,
            admins, operators, and donors
          </li>
          <li class="section__item">
            <strong>Backend API — Go:</strong> central entry point for application
            requests
          </li>
          <li class="section__item">
            <strong>Database — MongoDB:</strong> stores users, profiles, reports,
            operations, animal records, organizations, campaigns, donations, and audit
            data
          </li>
          <li class="section__item">
            <strong>Cache — Redis:</strong> supports temporary data, frequently accessed
            records, rate limiting, or session-related optimization
          </li>
          <li class="section__item">
            <strong>File storage — Cloud storage:</strong> stores uploaded files,
            photos, documents, and campaign media
          </li>
          <li class="section__item">
            <strong>External services:</strong> donation platform, notification services,
            and geolocation services
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ul>

    <img src="/images/stw2_5.c2.webp" alt="C1 diagram" />

    <ul class="section__list --parent">
      <li class="section__item">
        Core backend modules:
        <ul class="section__list">
          <li class="section__item">
            <strong>Auth / Identity:</strong> authentication, authorization, roles,
            and permissions
          </li>
          <li class="section__item">
            <strong>Profile:</strong> user profile information and role-specific user
            data
          </li>
          <li class="section__item">
            <strong>Organization / Team:</strong> organization structure, team membership,
            and professional assignment
          </li>
          <li class="section__item">
            <strong>Incident:</strong> public incident to be tracked and resolved
          </li>
          <li class="section__item">
            <strong>Report:</strong> reports, report status, report review, and aggregation
            of operations, incidents, and organizations
          </li>
          <li class="section__item">
            <strong>Operations:</strong> field rescue workflows and medical workflow
            coordination
          </li>
          <li class="section__item">
            <strong>Animal:</strong> animal case records, condition, status, and history
          </li>
          <li class="section__item">
            <strong>Campaign / Donation:</strong> donation campaigns, campaign progress,
            and donation-related records
          </li>
          <li class="section__item">
            <strong>Notification:</strong> event-based user notifications
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ul>

    <img src="/images/stw2_5.c3.webp" alt="C1 diagram" />

    <ul class="section__list --parent">
      <li class="section__item">
        Communication:
        <ul class="section__list">
          <li class="section__item">
            Frontend communicates with the backend through REST APIs
          </li>
          <li class="section__item">API contracts use JSON</li>
          <li class="section__item">
            The backend communicates with the database, cache, file storage, and
            external services
          </li>
          <li class="section__item">
            External services are accessed through integration layers to keep
            third-party logic isolated from core domain logic
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <!-- 6. Data Model & Behavior -->
  <section class="section__container">
    <h2 class="section__title">6. Data Model &amp; Behavior</h2>
    <p class="section__intro">
      A structured and flexible data model underpins the system, enabling
      consistent data handling, traceability, and support for complex workflows,
      with clearly defined entities, relationships, and lifecycle behaviors.
    </p>

    <ul class="section__list --parent">
      <li class="section__item">
        Core entities:
        <ul class="section__list">
          <li class="section__item">Incident, Report, MasterReport</li>
          <li class="section__item">FieldOperation and MedicalOperation</li>
          <li class="section__item">Animal</li>
          <li class="section__item">Campaign and Donation</li>
          <li class="section__item">Organization, Team, and User</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li class="section__item">
        Aggregation model:
        <ul class="section__list">
          <li class="section__item">Report → MasterReport → MegaReport</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li class="section__item">
        Data rules:
        <ul class="section__list">
          <li class="section__item">No hard deletes for auditability</li>
          <li class="section__item">
            Derived fields such as risk level and campaign progress
          </li>
          <li class="section__item">Time constraints, such as ≤ 365 days</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li class="section__item">
        RBAC:
        <ul class="section__list">
          <li class="section__item">Membership roles: Manager, Contributor</li>
          <li class="section__item">Functional roles: Vet, Ranger</li>
          <li class="section__item">Entity-level roles: Operation Lead</li>
          <li class="section__item">System roles: Admin</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li class="section__item">
        Key workflows:
        <ul class="section__list">
          <li class="section__item">
            Incident submission → validation → report creation
          </li>
          <li class="section__item">
            Report → operation assignment → execution
          </li>
          <li class="section__item">Campaign → donation → tracking</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li class="section__item">
        Lifecycle states:
        <ul class="section__list">
          <li class="section__item">Incident: Unverified → Resolved</li>
          <li class="section__item">Report: Draft → Closed</li>
          <li class="section__item">Operation: Unassigned → Completed</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ul>

    <div class="subsection__container">
      <h3 class="subsection__title">High-level ERD</h3>
      <img src="/images/stw2_6.erd.webp" alt="C1 diagram" />
    </div>
    <div class="subsection__container">
      <h3 class="subsection__title">Detailed ERD</h3>
      <img src="/images/stw2_6.umldata.webp" alt="C1 diagram" />
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- 7. Decisions & Trade-offs -->
  <section class="section__container">
    <h2 class="section__title">7. Decisions &amp; Trade-offs</h2>
    <p class="section__intro">
      Key architectural decisions prioritize simplicity, maintainability, and
      delivery speed over premature scalability, with explicit trade-offs made
      to balance flexibility, control, and system complexity.
    </p>

    <ul class="section__list --parent">
      <li class="section__item">
        Modular monolith vs microservices:
        <ul class="section__list">
          <li class="section__item">
            Chosen for simplicity and fast iteration
          </li>
          <li class="section__item">
            Trade-off: limited scalability compared with independently deployed
            services
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li class="section__item">
        MongoDB vs SQL:
        <ul class="section__list">
          <li class="section__item">
            Chosen for flexible and evolving schemas
          </li>
          <li class="section__item">
            Trade-off: weaker analytical querying compared with relational
            models
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li class="section__item">
        REST vs GraphQL:
        <ul class="section__list">
          <li class="section__item">
            Chosen for simplicity and standardization
          </li>
          <li class="section__item">Trade-off: less flexible data fetching</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li class="section__item">
        Stateful auth vs JWT:
        <ul class="section__list">
          <li class="section__item">Chosen for control and revocation</li>
          <li class="section__item">Trade-off: session management overhead</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li class="section__item">
        General principle: prioritize simplicity, maintainability, and delivery
        speed over premature scale.
      </li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <!-- 8. Reliability & Scalability -->
  <section class="section__container">
    <h2 class="section__title">8. Reliability &amp; Scalability</h2>
    <p class="section__intro">
      The system ensures reliability through validation, access control, and
      audit mechanisms, while supporting scalable growth through caching and
      future-ready architectural improvements.
    </p>

    <ul class="section__list --parent">
      <li class="section__item">
        Reliability:
        <ul class="section__list">
          <li class="section__item">Input validation and error handling</li>
          <li class="section__item">RBAC enforcement per request</li>
          <li class="section__item">Audit logs for all critical actions</li>
          <li class="section__item">Backup-based recovery</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li class="section__item">
        Availability:
        <ul class="section__list">
          <li class="section__item">Target &gt; 99.5% uptime</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li class="section__item">
        Scalability:
        <ul class="section__list">
          <li class="section__item">
            Horizontal scaling as a future-ready path
          </li>
          <li class="section__item">Redis for caching and rate limiting</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li class="section__item">
        Limitations:
        <ul class="section__list">
          <li class="section__item">
            No auto-scaling or multi-region failover in the MVP
          </li>
          <li class="section__item">No full observability stack in the MVP</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li class="section__item">
        Future improvements:
        <ul class="section__list">
          <li class="section__item">Event-driven architecture</li>
          <li class="section__item">Data sharding</li>
          <li class="section__item">Advanced monitoring and alerting</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ul>

    <div class="subsection__container">
      <h3 class="subsection__title">Future Architecture View</h3>
      <img src="/images/stw2_8.futurec2.webp" alt="C1 diagram" />
    </div>

    <div class="subsection__container">
      <h3 class="subsection__title">Reliability &amp; Failure Handling</h3>

      <div class="table__container">
        <table class="section__table">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Failure scenario</th>
              <th>Expected behavior</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>Notification provider unavailable</td>
              <td
                >Store notification attempt, retry later, and show no blocking
                error to the user</td
              >
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Donation provider webhook fails</td>
              <td
                >Log event, retry or verify status, and avoid duplicate donation
                records</td
              >
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Geolocation service unavailable</td>
              <td>Allow manual location input</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Image upload fails</td>
              <td>Keep report draft or return a clear retry message</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Database unavailable</td>
              <td>Return a safe error and do not accept partial operations</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Duplicate incident/report</td>
              <td>Allow admin merge or review instead of auto-delete</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- 9. Outcome & Learnings -->
  <section class="section__container">
    <h2 class="section__title">9. Outcome &amp; Learnings</h2>
    <p class="section__intro">
      The platform improves operational efficiency, data consistency, and
      coordination, while highlighting the importance of designing for
      real-world workflows, making explicit trade-offs, and building systems
      that can evolve into scalable platforms.
    </p>

    <ul class="section__list --parent">
      <li class="section__item">
        Impact:
        <ul class="section__list">
          <li class="section__item">Response time reduced to &lt; 2 hours</li>
          <li class="section__item">Volunteer participation &gt; 75%</li>
          <li class="section__item">Data completeness &gt; 90%</li>
          <li class="section__item">Improved transparency and trust</li>
          <li class="section__item">Centralized operational visibility</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li class="section__item">
        Outcome:
        <ul class="section__list">
          <li class="section__item">Strong domain modeling</li>
          <li class="section__item">Clear modular architecture</li>
          <li class="section__item">
            Balanced trade-offs for real-world constraints
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li class="section__item">
        Learnings:
        <ul class="section__list">
          <li class="section__item">
            Design for real workflows, not ideal ones
          </li>
          <li class="section__item">
            Structure NoSQL data carefully for predictability
          </li>
          <li class="section__item">Make trade-offs explicit</li>
          <li class="section__item">Communicate architecture clearly</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </section>
</Layout>
